00:07:33,450 --> 00:07:36,630
This turning point happened with Opus 4.5 in November,

142
00:07:36,630 --> 00:07:40,550
this major inflection point when the model was good enough

143
00:07:40,550 --> 00:07:43,230
that it could one-shot these apps.

144
00:07:43,230 --> 00:07:46,870
And it's still, if you even take Opus 4.7

145
00:07:46,870 --> 00:07:50,550
and you tell it to one-shot an app on Ethereum,

146
00:07:50,550 --> 00:07:52,070
it's gonna have a lot of troubles

147
00:07:52,070 --> 00:07:54,010
because Ethereum moves so fast

148
00:07:54,010 --> 00:07:56,710
and there's so many things that aren't built into the LLM,

149
00:07:56,710 --> 00:07:58,730
but we'll get to that in a little bit.

150
00:07:58,730 --> 00:08:01,830
I think what I wanna get to here is the evolution

151
00:08:01,830 --> 00:08:05,630
after this inflection point, after we had Opus 4.5,

152
00:08:05,630 --> 00:08:09,590
the next thing that came was these agent harnesses

153
00:08:09,590 --> 00:08:12,930
that sort of created these agents, right?

154
00:08:12,930 --> 00:08:15,550
Once you had an AI agent and you could talk to it,

155
00:08:15,550 --> 00:08:17,330
they weren't just chat bots anymore.

156
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:20,790
They were actually, you could spin up your open claw

157
00:08:20,790 --> 00:08:22,550
and you could talk to your open claw

158
00:08:22,550 --> 00:08:24,550
and it could control your computer.

159
00:08:24,550 --> 00:08:27,870
And so many things kind of shook loose from that

160
00:08:27,870 --> 00:08:32,710
and this is my favorite thing to build with.

161
00:08:32,710 --> 00:08:36,870
So with open claw, I have a whole army of agents

162
00:08:36,870 --> 00:08:38,470
inside my telegram.

163
00:08:38,470 --> 00:08:40,910
I used to write code with my fingers.

164
00:08:40,910 --> 00:08:42,110
I don't do that anymore.

165
00:08:42,110 --> 00:08:44,110
I just get on telegram and I say,

166
00:08:44,110 --> 00:08:46,830
hey agent, go build me this,

167
00:08:46,830 --> 00:08:50,270
or go add this feature to this website.

168
00:08:50,270 --> 00:08:52,270
And it's not just some website somewhere,

169
00:08:52,270 --> 00:08:54,790
it's actual things that you connect your wallet through,

170
00:08:54,790 --> 00:08:57,870
actual crypto apps, building smart contracts.

171
00:08:57,870 --> 00:08:59,310
So I have an army of agents

172
00:08:59,310 --> 00:09:01,630
that are deploying smart contract apps.

173
00:09:01,630 --> 00:09:04,150
I even have an agent pipeline

174
00:09:04,150 --> 00:09:07,830
where people can hire my agents to build things

175
00:09:07,830 --> 00:09:11,550
and then they can pay in USDC on chain.

176
00:09:11,550 --> 00:09:15,990
And my agent has built a couple of smart contracts

177
00:09:15,990 --> 00:09:18,190
that have like a quarter of a million dollars

178
00:09:18,190 --> 00:09:19,070
in them right now.

179
00:09:19,070 --> 00:09:21,330
And a human didn't even look at the code.

180
00:09:21,330 --> 00:09:23,530
Now, this is dangerous and a little scary

181
00:09:23,530 --> 00:09:25,370
and everyone shouldn't do this,

182
00:09:25,370 --> 00:09:27,050
but I'm just talking about

183
00:09:27,050 --> 00:09:29,650
this is getting to be more and more accessible

184
00:09:29,650 --> 00:09:33,090
and someone with a good idea and a good skill file

185
00:09:33,090 --> 00:09:36,450
and a good agent can build things right away.

186
00:09:36,450 --> 00:09:38,570
So what is an agent, right?

187
00:09:38,570 --> 00:09:42,450
An agent is kind of just like an LLM with a game loop

188
00:09:42,450 --> 00:09:44,890
and a set of tools, right?

189
00:09:44,890 --> 00:09:46,130
You can kind of think of that loop

190
00:09:46,130 --> 00:09:49,610
as just like a control structure where you're prompting it

191
00:09:49,610 --> 00:09:51,370
and then it has some memory.

192
00:09:51,370 --> 00:09:53,590
And agents are really good

193
00:09:53,590 --> 00:09:56,170
for really like open-ended tasks, right?

194
00:09:56,170 --> 00:09:58,210
So when you're going to build something,

195
00:09:58,210 --> 00:10:01,110
you don't have to give it a single feature anymore.

196
00:10:01,110 --> 00:10:03,210
You don't have to say center the div,

197
00:10:03,210 --> 00:10:05,190
put this text there, right?

198
00:10:05,190 --> 00:10:07,810
An agent is good at sort of starting to figure out

199
00:10:07,810 --> 00:10:09,610
these more general purpose things

200
00:10:09,610 --> 00:10:11,410
and you can start to talk to your agent

201
00:10:11,410 --> 00:10:15,290
with these nice models at a higher level of abstraction.

202
00:10:15,290 --> 00:10:19,090
And so my setup, I have a bunch of OpenClaw

203
00:10:19,090 --> 00:10:21,290
or Hermes or some other harness,

204
00:10:21,290 --> 00:10:23,410
but right now I'm using OpenClaw.

205
00:10:23,410 --> 00:10:26,090
And what I do is for every project,

206
00:10:26,090 --> 00:10:30,770
I set up an OpenClaw agent that is the product manager.

207
00:10:30,770 --> 00:10:32,690
And then I set up an OpenClaw agent

208
00:10:32,690 --> 00:10:37,330
with the same shared workspace that is the builder.

209
00:10:37,330 --> 00:10:38,730
Usually that's Opus.

210
00:10:38,730 --> 00:10:42,010
So I'll have Opus 4.7 as my builder

211
00:10:42,010 --> 00:10:44,290
and then I'll have a product manager.

212
00:10:44,290 --> 00:10:46,250
Sometimes I have two product managers.

213
00:10:46,250 --> 00:10:49,490
Sometimes I'll have Sonnet as one product manager

214
00:10:49,490 --> 00:10:52,650
and sometimes I'll have Minimax M27 as another.

215
00:10:52,650 --> 00:10:54,850
And it's like a very, very cheap model.

216
00:10:54,850 --> 00:10:56,810
So if I'm just like chatting with my code,

217
00:10:56,810 --> 00:11:00,450
telling it to do a get push, I'm probably using Minimax.

218
00:11:00,450 --> 00:11:03,230
If I'm chatting and I'm thinking of how we're gonna go

219
00:11:03,230 --> 00:11:05,010
about making this next feature,

220
00:11:05,010 --> 00:11:06,650
I'm probably talking to Sonnet.

221
00:11:06,650 --> 00:11:08,370
And then when it goes to build the thing,

222
00:11:08,370 --> 00:11:09,990
it will push it all to Opus

223
00:11:09,990 --> 00:11:11,970
and that agent will build the thing

224
00:11:11,970 --> 00:11:14,610
and then Sonnet will probably run some tests.

225
00:11:14,610 --> 00:11:17,770
But what's really nice about having a set of agents

226
00:11:17,770 --> 00:11:20,890
for one project is anytime I need to go back

227
00:11:20,890 --> 00:11:23,770
to that project, I can just go back to that Telegram channel

228
00:11:23,770 --> 00:11:26,890
and say, hey, let's add this new feature

229
00:11:26,890 --> 00:11:29,330
and it already has all of the context for that

230
00:11:29,330 --> 00:11:32,090
and it can jump right in and build that thing.

231
00:11:32,090 --> 00:11:34,730
And I always find myself kind of wavering

232
00:11:34,730 --> 00:11:38,170
between efficient and effective.

233
00:11:38,170 --> 00:11:42,050
And what I mean by that is my agents will be really effective

234
00:11:42,050 --> 00:11:45,050
at building something, but it will be very expensive.

235
00:11:45,050 --> 00:11:47,690
I'll spend hundreds of dollars in one day.

236
00:11:47,690 --> 00:11:49,890
And then, so I'll try to make it more efficient

237
00:11:49,890 --> 00:11:52,570
and I'll try to use Minimax M7 more.

238
00:11:52,570 --> 00:11:54,450
And then it's just not as effective

239
00:11:54,450 --> 00:11:55,850
and it messes up a little bit.

240
00:11:55,850 --> 00:11:57,730
And then I'm back to paying more

241
00:11:57,730 --> 00:11:59,770
and I kind of find myself kind of going

242
00:11:59,770 --> 00:12:01,290
between these two things.

243
00:12:01,290 --> 00:12:02,530
And I think what you need to do

244
00:12:02,530 --> 00:12:05,450
is have your general purpose agent that you're talking to

245
00:12:05,450 --> 00:12:07,530
but understand that it's expensive

246
00:12:07,530 --> 00:12:10,690
and then have specific agents for specific jobs

247
00:12:10,690 --> 00:12:13,970
and try to have them be more efficient.

248
00:12:13,970 --> 00:12:16,130
So you have your general purpose

249
00:12:16,130 --> 00:12:18,810
that's very effective and expensive

250
00:12:18,810 --> 00:12:23,490
and then have your specific agents that do specific things

251
00:12:23,490 --> 00:12:25,690
and you can make them more and more efficient

252
00:12:25,690 --> 00:12:27,890
with their workflows.

253
00:12:27,890 --> 00:12:30,370
Okay, so the million dollar question right now

254
00:12:30,370 --> 00:12:33,250
is how you give your agent a wallet.

255
00:12:33,250 --> 00:12:34,970
It loves private keys, right?

256
00:12:34,970 --> 00:12:37,490
I can give my OpenClaw a private key

257
00:12:37,490 --> 00:12:39,690
and it can use Foundry and Cast

258
00:12:39,690 --> 00:12:43,530
and it can go send money here and put money there

259
00:12:43,530 --> 00:12:46,610
and it's very fast and very good at doing that.

260
00:12:46,610 --> 00:12:48,690
But there's a little scary part about that.

261
00:12:48,690 --> 00:12:50,570
My agent will get in a chat room

262
00:12:50,570 --> 00:12:51,730
and be chatting with someone

263
00:12:51,730 --> 00:12:55,810
and send over the private key if they ask nicely for it.

264
00:12:55,810 --> 00:12:57,370
So you have to be very careful

265
00:12:57,370 --> 00:12:59,010
if you give your agent a private key

266
00:12:59,010 --> 00:13:01,410
to just keep a tiny amount of money in it,

267
00:13:01,410 --> 00:13:04,370
just enough for gas to do what it needs to do.

268
00:13:04,370 --> 00:13:07,250
You can give your agent a browser wallet

269
00:13:07,290 --> 00:13:10,890
and that like MetaMask or Kohaku who's coming out soon

270
00:13:10,890 --> 00:13:14,650
and it can use that, but it's a little clunky

271
00:13:14,650 --> 00:13:16,210
and it's still trying to figure that out.

272
00:13:16,210 --> 00:13:18,610
So we're not quite there with that, but it works.

273
00:13:18,610 --> 00:13:20,410
My agent can use a MetaMask.

274
00:13:20,410 --> 00:13:22,570
It does it every day when it needs to.

275
00:13:22,570 --> 00:13:26,490
It even wrote its own app and then used its MetaMask

276
00:13:26,490 --> 00:13:29,730
to interface with the app all night long.

277
00:13:29,730 --> 00:13:30,570
It was moderating.

278
00:13:30,570 --> 00:13:32,410
It was a PFP marketplace

279
00:13:32,410 --> 00:13:34,250
and it was moderating the marketplace,

280
00:13:34,290 --> 00:13:36,970
making sure nothing nasty got posted to it.

281
00:13:37,810 --> 00:13:40,890
What we really need though is something like a passkey.

282
00:13:40,890 --> 00:13:43,810
I think the best agent wallet would be something

283
00:13:43,810 --> 00:13:46,050
where an agent can have something signed

284
00:13:46,050 --> 00:13:48,010
like a transaction signed,

285
00:13:48,010 --> 00:13:50,170
but then it can't leak the private key.

286
00:13:50,170 --> 00:13:53,050
It needs access to be able to use the private key,

287
00:13:53,050 --> 00:13:54,970
but it can't leak the private key.

288
00:13:54,970 --> 00:13:57,490
And I think that's the million dollar question right now.

289
00:13:57,490 --> 00:14:00,090
And there's a lot of people building agent wallets.

290
00:14:00,090 --> 00:14:02,650
If you get on Twitter and start searching for agent wallets,

291
00:14:02,650 --> 00:14:04,490
you're going to find a lot of them.

292
00:14:04,490 --> 00:14:07,730
One of my favorite ways to have my agent use crypto

293
00:14:07,730 --> 00:14:09,610
is with a multisig.

294
00:14:09,610 --> 00:14:13,050
I'll have my agent either deploy its own multisig

295
00:14:13,050 --> 00:14:15,250
or talk to my gnosis safe.

296
00:14:15,250 --> 00:14:16,690
And what I'll tell it,

297
00:14:16,690 --> 00:14:19,250
I'll tell it some intent in plain English.

298
00:14:19,250 --> 00:14:21,090
Please go swap this for that,

299
00:14:21,090 --> 00:14:25,730
or please send these tokens to ATG or Vitalik.ETH.

300
00:14:25,730 --> 00:14:28,090
And it will basically send me back a link

301
00:14:28,090 --> 00:14:29,170
and I'll click that link

302
00:14:29,170 --> 00:14:32,210
and I'll go sign the transaction in my multisig.

303
00:14:32,210 --> 00:14:34,090
So there's a lot of different flavors

304
00:14:34,090 --> 00:14:35,970
of agentic wallets right now,

305
00:14:35,970 --> 00:14:40,210
but this is definitely a hot topic to keep an eye on.

306
00:14:40,210 --> 00:14:42,210
Okay, when you're building,

307
00:14:42,210 --> 00:14:45,650
it really comes down to having a good AI model

308
00:14:45,650 --> 00:14:47,210
and a good harness.

309
00:14:47,210 --> 00:14:48,370
Right now, we're just going to say

310
00:14:48,370 --> 00:14:52,730
that the state of the art is Opus 4.7

311
00:14:52,730 --> 00:14:57,730
and Hermes or OpenClaw or Clodcode or Cursor.

312
00:14:57,890 --> 00:14:59,410
Any of these things are good.

313
00:14:59,410 --> 00:15:01,970
So let's say you have Cursor or you have Clodcode

314
00:15:01,970 --> 00:15:03,010
or you have OpenClaw.

315
00:15:03,010 --> 00:15:05,330
Any of these are great.

316
00:15:05,330 --> 00:15:08,090
Select Sonnet or Opus,

317
00:15:08,090 --> 00:15:09,930
depending on how much money you want to spend,

318
00:15:09,930 --> 00:15:11,370
maybe a cheaper one you could try,

319
00:15:11,370 --> 00:15:13,370
maybe some local AI, right?

320
00:15:13,370 --> 00:15:15,250
Always try to get that local AI going

321
00:15:15,250 --> 00:15:17,890
and it's always awesome when it's free.

322
00:15:17,890 --> 00:15:20,890
You just got to have a lot of local hardware.

323
00:15:20,890 --> 00:15:25,770
But what you do is you're going to need skill files, okay?

324
00:15:25,770 --> 00:15:27,850
And if you're building anything right now

325
00:15:27,850 --> 00:15:30,570
that agents may want to interface with,

326
00:15:30,570 --> 00:15:33,050
you absolutely should have a skill file.

327
00:15:33,050 --> 00:15:37,330
You should have a slash skill.md on your website.

328
00:15:37,330 --> 00:15:42,250
So whatever your website is, something.com slash skill.md.

329
00:15:42,250 --> 00:15:45,130
And inside that skill.md, it should be plain text,

330
00:15:45,130 --> 00:15:49,010
just marked down, that explains in plain English

331
00:15:49,010 --> 00:15:53,530
everything that an agent can do and where to interface

332
00:15:53,530 --> 00:15:55,730
and what the API routes are.

333
00:15:55,730 --> 00:15:58,650
Basically, an agent can land on your website,

334
00:15:58,650 --> 00:16:03,330
go to skills.md and quickly learn about it.

335
00:16:03,330 --> 00:16:04,770
So also there's code.

336
00:16:04,770 --> 00:16:07,930
If you give your agent code, it's more deterministic.

337
00:16:07,930 --> 00:16:10,450
It's really good at using deterministic code

338
00:16:10,450 --> 00:16:11,370
to get things done.

339
00:16:11,370 --> 00:16:14,570
So anything you find yourself doing often,

340
00:16:14,570 --> 00:16:18,010
quit telling your general purpose agent to do that thing

341
00:16:18,010 --> 00:16:19,850
and write a piece of code for it

342
00:16:19,850 --> 00:16:21,730
and have it be a tool for your agent

343
00:16:21,730 --> 00:16:23,650
so your agent can just call it.

344
00:16:23,650 --> 00:16:27,250
Okay, so the skill file that I really want to show off today

345
00:16:27,250 --> 00:16:29,570
is ethskills.com.

346
00:16:29,570 --> 00:16:32,090
Ethskills.com is a skill library

347
00:16:32,090 --> 00:16:34,930
that I've been building with my team,

348
00:16:34,930 --> 00:16:37,530
the Builder Growth team at the EF.

349
00:16:37,530 --> 00:16:40,370
And it's a very highly curated skill library

350
00:16:40,370 --> 00:16:42,810
that helps upgrade your agent

351
00:16:42,810 --> 00:16:46,650
to be able to deploy things on Ethereum.

352
00:16:46,650 --> 00:16:51,650
There's a large delta between what the LLM knows

353
00:16:51,890 --> 00:16:54,610
and what has happened on main net Ethereum.

354
00:16:54,610 --> 00:16:56,050
There's things like gas

355
00:16:56,050 --> 00:16:57,530
and things like how to ship

356
00:16:57,530 --> 00:17:01,290
and what different tools you need.

357
00:17:01,290 --> 00:17:04,890
This is an interesting thing that the LLMs don't know

358
00:17:04,890 --> 00:17:05,890
when you wake them up

359
00:17:05,890 --> 00:17:07,770
and you have to give them a skill file.

360
00:17:07,770 --> 00:17:10,850
And this skill file gets them from I'm waking up

361
00:17:10,850 --> 00:17:13,570
and I don't know about anything in the last two years

362
00:17:13,570 --> 00:17:16,890
to I know exactly how to deploy on main net Ethereum

363
00:17:16,890 --> 00:17:18,570
and I know how to use the tools.

364
00:17:18,570 --> 00:17:23,570
So ethskills.com for giving your agent the ability to build.

365
00:17:23,690 --> 00:17:25,570
You can have cloud code, you can have cursor,

366
00:17:25,570 --> 00:17:28,050
you can have open claw, and you can just tell it,

367
00:17:28,050 --> 00:17:31,090
go to ethskills.com and learn how to do this

368
00:17:31,090 --> 00:17:34,090
and then let's go build X or Y or Z.

369
00:17:34,090 --> 00:17:37,250
And there's a QR code there for you to go to ethskills.

370
00:17:37,250 --> 00:17:40,570
And what it looks like is just this big block of text, right?

371
00:17:40,570 --> 00:17:44,170
It's this wild kind of like, oh, I can't even look at it.

372
00:17:44,170 --> 00:17:45,690
It's probably, you probably can't even read it

373
00:17:45,690 --> 00:17:47,090
on the screen.

374
00:17:47,090 --> 00:17:49,810
But it's just a bunch of information in plain text

375
00:17:49,810 --> 00:17:52,450
and it helps the agent learn all the different things

376
00:17:52,450 --> 00:17:53,610
that it needs to know.

377
00:17:53,610 --> 00:17:55,330
And we've curated this list.

378
00:17:55,330 --> 00:17:58,050
So these things that are in this are things

379
00:17:58,050 --> 00:18:00,050
that the LLM doesn't already know.

380
00:18:00,050 --> 00:18:02,610
If it already knew this, we'd be polluting the context.

381
00:18:02,610 --> 00:18:05,450
So you want to have really important things.

382
00:18:05,450 --> 00:18:07,330
And there's a huge list of context here.

383
00:18:07,330 --> 00:18:09,210
This is my craziest slide.

384
00:18:09,210 --> 00:18:12,210
We've got, you know, how to ship the protocol wallets.

385
00:18:12,210 --> 00:18:13,810
There's so many things here,

386
00:18:13,810 --> 00:18:15,810
but this teaches your agent everything

387
00:18:15,810 --> 00:18:17,550
about building on Ethereum.

388
00:18:18,450 --> 00:18:20,090
Okay, so how do you use it?

389
00:18:20,090 --> 00:18:21,170
This is the best part.

390
00:18:21,170 --> 00:18:22,970
You don't have to install anything.

391
00:18:22,970 --> 00:18:26,730
You can just tell your agent to go read each skills

392
00:18:26,730 --> 00:18:29,210
and it can even, you can even tell it like,

393
00:18:29,210 --> 00:18:30,370
go read each skills

394
00:18:30,370 --> 00:18:32,470
and make sure there's nothing bad about this.

395
00:18:32,470 --> 00:18:34,090
Make sure there's nothing nefarious

396
00:18:34,090 --> 00:18:36,750
and it can look at it and make sure there's nothing bad.

397
00:18:36,750 --> 00:18:40,170
So just tell your agent to go read each skills.

398
00:18:40,170 --> 00:18:42,370
Eventually, you might even want to tell your agent

399
00:18:42,370 --> 00:18:45,950
to install each skills and it will take in all these files,

400
00:18:45,950 --> 00:18:47,350
but they're just text files.

401
00:18:47,350 --> 00:18:48,190
It's so cool.

402
00:18:48,190 --> 00:18:49,590
There's nothing to ask to run.

403
00:18:49,590 --> 00:18:52,450
You can just bring in this like library

404
00:18:52,450 --> 00:18:55,490
into your thing that's just a bunch of text files

405
00:18:55,490 --> 00:18:57,570
and it learns Kung Fu immediately

406
00:18:57,570 --> 00:19:01,890
and it can build all kinds of cool smart contract apps.

407
00:19:01,890 --> 00:19:06,890
So this is for you as the user.

408
00:19:07,250 --> 00:19:10,730
Right, the AI needs each skills,

409
00:19:10,730 --> 00:19:13,610
but the human still needs the concepts.

410
00:19:13,610 --> 00:19:17,410
So you as the human should go to speed run Ethereum.

411
00:19:17,410 --> 00:19:20,410
So speed run Ethereum is a great place for you,

412
00:19:20,410 --> 00:19:23,050
the human to learn the concepts.

413
00:19:23,050 --> 00:19:27,490
One really critical concept is the liquidation method

414
00:19:27,490 --> 00:19:30,330
in over collateralized lending.

415
00:19:30,330 --> 00:19:31,770
Now there's a lot of words there

416
00:19:31,770 --> 00:19:33,470
and it sounds pretty complicated,

417
00:19:33,470 --> 00:19:36,590
but basically what happens is there's this automatic thing

418
00:19:36,590 --> 00:19:39,330
that happens that makes sure that a loan

419
00:19:39,330 --> 00:19:41,570
never goes underwater.

420
00:19:41,570 --> 00:19:44,650
The protocol always stays whole.

421
00:19:44,650 --> 00:19:46,930
And the way that it runs this thing

422
00:19:46,930 --> 00:19:49,090
is two very important concepts.

423
00:19:49,090 --> 00:19:51,690
First of all, the rules are written correctly.

424
00:19:51,690 --> 00:19:52,650
And second of all,

425
00:19:52,650 --> 00:19:55,090
there's an incentive to push the button.

426
00:19:55,090 --> 00:19:57,010
Anybody out there can push this button

427
00:19:57,010 --> 00:19:59,690
to liquidate a loan when it's liquidatable.
